  <section>
    <h2>The Roughness Index</h2>
    <p>The centrepiece of Dip Report is the <strong>Roughness Index</strong> ‚Äî a custom safety algorithm designed specifically for sea swimmers. It analyses wave height, wind speed, swell period, and swell direction simultaneously and produces a single score from <strong>0 (Calm) to 100 (Unsafe)</strong>.</p>
    <div class="r-scale">
      <div class="r-row"><div class="r-dot" style="background:#22C55E"></div><div class="r-name" style="color:#22C55E">Calm</div><div class="r-desc">0‚Äì25 ¬∑ Ideal swimming conditions. Low swell, light winds, manageable waves.</div></div>
      <div class="r-row"><div class="r-dot" style="background:#3B82F6"></div><div class="r-name" style="color:#3B82F6">Medium</div><div class="r-desc">26‚Äì55 ¬∑ Swimmable for experienced swimmers. Some chop or swell present.</div></div>
      <div class="r-row"><div class="r-dot" style="background:#F97316"></div><div class="r-name" style="color:#F97316">Rough</div><div class="r-desc">56‚Äì80 ¬∑ Challenging conditions. Caution advised, especially for beginners.</div></div>
      <div class="r-row"><div class="r-dot" style="background:#EF4444"></div><div class="r-name" style="color:#EF4444">Unsafe</div><div class="r-desc">81‚Äì100 ¬∑ Not recommended. High waves, strong winds, or dangerous swell.</div></div>
    </div>
    <p>An onshore swell of 2m is treated very differently to an offshore swell of the same height ‚Äî because for a swimmer, it is. The index is recalculated for every hour of the 7-day forecast.</p>
  </section>

